International Journal of Radiation Oncology*Biology*Physics

Volume 74, Issue 5, 1 August 2009, Pages 1609-1616

Physics Contribution
Microscopic Gold Particle-Based Fiducial Markers for Proton Therapy of Prostate Cancer

Author links open overlay panel, , , , , , , , , , , , ,
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijrobp.2009.02.076Get rights and content

Purpose

We examined the feasibility of using fiducial markers composed of microscopic gold particles and human-compatible polymers as a means to overcome current problems with conventional macroscopic gold fiducial markers, such as dose reduction and artifact generation, in proton therapy for prostate cancer.

Methods and Materials

We examined two types of gold particle fiducial marker interactions: that with diagnostic X-rays and with a therapeutic proton beam. That is, we qualitatively and quantitatively compared the radiographic visibility of conventional gold and gold particle fiducial markers and the CT artifacts and dose reduction associated with their use.

Results

The gold particle fiducials could be easily distinguished from high-density structures, such as the pelvic bone, in diagnostic X-rays but were nearly transparent to a proton beam. The proton dose distribution was distorted <5% by the gold particle fiducials with a 4.9% normalized gold density; this was the case even in the worst configuration (i.e., parallel alignment with a single-direction proton beam). In addition, CT artifacts were dramatically reduced for the gold particle mixture.

Conclusion

Mixtures of microscopic gold particles and human-compatible polymers have excellent potential as fiducial markers for proton therapy for prostate cancer. These include good radiographic visibility, low distortion of the depth-dose distribution, and few CT artifacts.

Introduction

The clinical outcome of external-beam radiotherapy (EBRT) is closely related to the accuracy with which the beam is aligned with the target and to the precision of beam shaping 1, 2, 3. Precise beam shaping and accurate alignment have been achieved with intensity-modulated radiotherapy (IMRT) and image-guided radiotherapy (IGRT), respectively. However, in the treatment of prostate cancer using an image-guided technique, fiducial markers are also frequently implanted in the prostate to verify its location 4, 5, 6, 7, both to eliminate uncertainties regarding position resulting from prostate motion and to avoid patient setup errors 8, 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15.

These fiducial markers should satisfy the following requirements for the proton therapy treatment of prostate cancer: (1) good radiographic visibility in diagnostic X-rays, (2) no distortion of the delivered dose, (3) minimal artifacts in the CT images used for treatment planning, and (4) no migration during treatment. Conventional gold fiducial markers do not fully satisfy these requirements. A particular problem with these markers is that the radiation dose behind them is significantly distorted, resulting in less effective tumor cell kill. In particular, recent studies have shown that conventional gold fiducials cause a >20% dose reduction in photon therapy 16, 17 and an 85% dose reduction in proton therapy (18). Conventional gold fiducial markers also create artifacts in CT images, resulting in inaccurate treatment planning 19, 20, 21. Thus, there is an urgent need for better fiducial markers, especially for proton therapy. Recently, researchers have begun to investigate the influence of metallic materials and the inhomogeneity correction necessary to reduce range uncertainty in proton therapy 22, 23, 24. However, the CT artifacts are presumably inevitable as long as a macroscopic (a few mm3) gold lump is used as a fiducial marker. The most effective way to overcome the problem with artifacts is to remove the influence of inhomogeneous materials intrinsically.

To reduce distortion of the depth-dose distribution, early studies explored the use of various kinds of low-atomic-number metals as fiducial markers (18). In this study, we focused on the use of microscopic gold particles as fiducial markers for proton therapy for prostate cancer, reasoning that the inclusion of low numbers of gold atoms in a fiducial would reduce multiple proton scattering. In this way, the number of large-angle-scattered protons would decrease sufficiently to make the dose shadow produced by the gold particle mixture disappear. We also hypothesized that small gold particles used as fiducial markers would reduce CT artifacts because the periodic “lattice” created by the gold atoms would not be sufficient to give rise to significant X-ray diffraction within a single gold particle.

Methods and Materials

Phantom

Two kinds of interactions were investigated: (1) that of a conventional macroscopic gold fiducial or a mixture of microscopic gold particles with diagnostic X-rays and (2) that of these fiducials with a therapeutic proton beam. In the former interaction, the visibility of the markers and the CT artifacts created by them were assessed; in the latter, the dose distortions produced by the markers were measured. The interaction properties were compared for both proton and photon beams using a phantom (Fig. 1).

The macroscopic gold fiducial marker used in this study had a diameter of 1.2 mm and a length of 3.0 mm. The gold particles were <25 μm in diameter, >99% pure, and shaped as flakes. The gold particles were mixed with silicone paste to make a mixture of microscopic gold particles. For proper comparison with the macroscopic gold fiducials, the gold particle mixtures were embedded in small holes made in a 30 cm (length) × 30 cm (width) × 3 cm (height) acrylic plate, as shown in Fig. 1. Five pairs of holes (5 cm apart) were carved in the acrylic plate: one pair for macroscopic gold fiducial markers, three for gold particle fiducials with different mass particle concentrations, and one for pure silicone paste. Two holes were drilled orthogonally in each pair so that one marker was aligned parallel to the direction of the proton beam and the other was aligned perpendicular to it. This enabled the directional effect of the markers to be examined. Three concentrations of gold particles were tested: 50 mg, 100 mg, and 150 mg (mixed uniformly with 0.1 mL of silicone paste); these concentrations corresponded to 2.5%, 4.9%, and 7.2% normalized mass densities of gold particles, respectively. The normalized gold mass density was defined as the ratio of the mass density of gold particles in a mixture to that of a conventional gold fiducial marker (19.3 g/cm3).

Diagnostic X-ray radiographs

We first assessed the radiographic visibility of the macroscopic gold fiducials and the fiducials made up of varying concentrations of microscopic gold particles in diagnostic X-rays. Two-dimensional (2D) radiographs were obtained through an amorphous silicone detector driven by a digital imaging positioning system (DIPS; IBA, Louvain-la-Neuve, Belgium). The total thickness of the phantom was about 32 cm, similar to the lateral thickness of the human body. To represent the hipbones, 8-cm-thick bone-equivalent phantoms (a 4-cm-thick bone phantom plus a 4-cm-thick bone-equivalent phantom) were added around the acrylic plate (18). The X-ray exposure parameters used to acquire the 2D radiographs in the lateral direction were as follows: tube voltage, 110 kVp; tube current, 160 mA; irradiation time, 1 s. The minimum entrance dose of the X-ray required to see the images of the three types of gold particle mixtures was about 0.09 cGy. The visibility of the markers was also tested using a humanoid phantom (Alderson Rando Phantom; Alderson Research Laboratories, New York, NY) in the anterior-posterior (AP) and lateral directions under the diagnostic conditions used for prostate cancer: 100 kVp and 160 mAs in the AP direction, 120 kVp and 160 mAs in the lateral direction.

In three-dimensional (3D) radiographs, the acrylic phantom shown in Fig. 1 was scanned using a CT simulator (Ultra-Z; Philips Medical Systems, Best, The Netherlands). To achieve this, the acrylic phantom was inserted between a solid-water phantom (30 × 30 × 5 cm) and a bone phantom (30 × 30 × 4 cm) to allow the CT numbers of the solid water phantom and the bone phantom to be measured at the same time. The slice thickness was 1 mm, and the pixel resolution was 512 × 512. The scanned images were read on an Eclipse system (Version 8.0; Varian Medical Systems, Palo Alto, CA), which is the Varian radiation therapy planning system. The CT numbers for the gold particle fiducials, the macroscopic gold fiducial, and the bone phantom were then compared. We also compared the CT artifacts created by the markers to determine the mass concentration effects of the gold particle fiducials.

Proton radiographs and measurement of depth-dose distributions

The interactions of the proton beam with the macroscopic gold fiducial and the gold particle fiducials were measured on film radiographs. In these measurements, all markers on the acrylic phantom were arrayed in a plane perpendicular to the proton beam, and Gafchromic EBT film (International Specialty Products, Wayne, NJ) was attached to the acrylic phantom in parallel with the beam. The proton beam was propagated from the side opposite the film. The acrylic phantom and the EBT film were immersed in a 3D water phantom (RFA 3D-Servo; Scanditronix Wellhöfer, Schwarzenbruck, Germany) such that all markers were located in the middle of the spread-out Bragg peak (SOBP). The proton range and the width of SOBP in water were 21 g/cm2 and 8 g/cm2, respectively (typical conditions for the treatment of prostate cancer at the National Cancer Center of Korea). The proton field size was 25 cm in diameter so that all markers would be irradiated simultaneously.

The depth-dose distributions behind the markers were measured using a p-type silicone diode (Stereotactic Detector DEB050; Scanditronix Medial, Uppsala, Sweden) with an active volume of 0.017 mm3, and the distortions of the distributions were compared quantitatively. Every marker was positioned on the central axis of the proton beam so that the diode detector was exposed to the same scattering conditions of the proton beam for every measurement. The detector was on the beam axis, and measurement was performed along the direction of beam propagation. To ensure precise alignment between every marker and the detector, we obtained 2D radiographs with the help of the DIPS. Because the two markers with the same gold weight were embedded orthogonally, it was possible to examine the dependence of the dose distortion on marker direction.

Results

A 2D diagnostic X-ray image and several CT images of the various gold particle fiducials are presented in Fig. 2, Fig. 3, respectively. Although the gold particle mixtures had very low mass concentrations of gold compared with the macroscopic gold fiducial, they could be easily distinguished from the bony background on 2D diagnostic X-ray images, although the gold particle fiducial with the highest gold density seemed to be the most visible, as shown in Fig. 2.

As shown in Fig. 3, the CT numbers for the gold particle fiducials of different mass concentrations could be read, assuming that the gold particles were uniformly distributed inside the fiducial. The correlation between gold concentrations and corresponding maximum CT numbers is shown in Fig. 4. The least gold concentration was 1.0% with respect to the mass density of the conventional gold fiducial, yet its CT number was at least fourfold higher than that of the surrounding bone phantom. In contrast, although the highest gold concentration was 7.2%, its CT number was more than half the CT number of the conventional gold fiducial. This showed that the CT number was proportional to the mass concentration of gold particles. In other words, the contrast between the bone phantom and the gold particle fiducial improved as the gold concentration increased. Therefore, the gold particle fiducials met the requirement for good radiographic visibility. In addition, the CT number was not linearly related to the gold concentration; instead, there was a large gain in the CT number for the gold particle fiducial with the lowest concentration of gold. The fact that the gold particle fiducial with the low concentration of gold showed a sufficient CT value makes it useful for preventing dose distortion.

Figure 3 shows that there were intense artifacts around the macroscopic gold fiducial, whereas the intensity of the artifacts around the gold particle fiducials was much less. CT artifacts tended to decrease as the gold concentration of the fiducial decreased. This showed that it would be possible to optimize the mass concentration of gold particles by taking into consideration both the radiographic visibility of the fiducial and the CT artifacts created by the fiducial. An objective of this optimization process will be to achieve positioning resolution of the markers, which should be minimized to reduce patient positioning error. Positioning resolution is affected by radiographic visibility and CT artifacts, with the latter having a contrary effect on radiographic visibility and hence on positioning resolution. Therefore, positioning resolution can be minimized. In principle, minimizing the positioning resolution of the gold particle-based fiducial markers would involve optimizing the gold particle concentration.

Figure 5 shows proton radiographs of the macroscopic gold fiducial and the gold particle fiducial on planes parallel to the proton beam. In contrast to the X-ray radiograph, however, dose shadows were not observed behind the gold particle fiducials, but they were clearly present behind the macroscopic gold fiducials. In the film dosimetry study, some overdose was also found in the intersecting regions of straightly propagating protons and scattered protons from the macroscopic gold fiducial, but this overdose was not observed around the gold particle fiducials. The transverse size of the dose shadow was comparable to that of the gold fiducial, and the longitudinal length of the shadow was approximately 3–4 cm. The volume of the underdosed region for a perpendicularly aligned gold fiducial was about 0.1 mL, which can be approximately calculated from the transverse area and the longitudinal length of the dose shadow shown in Fig. 5.

We then measured the depth-dose distribution behind each marker with a diode detector (Fig. 6). This revealed that pure silicone paste (a reference substance) had a negligible effect on the distribution. The dose distributions for the parallel- and perpendicular-aligned markers are shown in Fig. 6a and 6b, respectively. As with the proton radiographs, there was a large dose reduction behind the macroscopic gold fiducial. Specifically, the ratio of the dose reduction to the average SOBP dose was 46% for parallel alignment and 23% for perpendicular alignment. In contrast, the dose reduction behind the gold particle fiducials was small. In particular, the maximum dose reduction for the gold particle fiducial with the 7.2% normalized gold density was at most 9% for the parallel alignment and 5% for the perpendicular alignment conditions.

Figure 3 shows the extent to which, qualitatively, the gold particle fiducials cause fewer CT artifacts. We also quantified the artifacts in a representative CT slice image of each marker, as shown in Fig. 3, by counting the pixels with the same CT numbers after excluding the artifact seeds (Fig. 7). The pure acrylic plate (0% Au) served as a reference, and pixels outside this reference region were regarded as artifacts. Pixels associated with the gold fiducial and the mixtures themselves were excluded during counting to consider only the pure artifacts. Nine pixels were excluded for each marker, and the size of each pixel was 0.9375 × 0.9375 mm2. The histogram of each marker had 7,486 pixels. The gold fiducial had 775 artifactual pixels and the 7.2% (w/w), 4.9% (w/w), and 2.5% gold particle fiducials had 142, 61, and 8 artifactual pixels, respectively. We thus quantitatively verified that the number and extent of CT artifacts was reduced as the gold concentration decreased.

Discussion

A previous study by Newhauser et al.(18) sought to identify prostate fiducial markers that are radiographically visible in the pelvis but that create dose shadows of ≤10% when the prostate is treated with a standard lateral-opposed pair of proton beams. Our study aimed to remove the dose shadow intrinsically by using a mixture of microscopic gold particles for the fiducial. Our results indicated that a gold particle mixture with a 4.9% normalized gold density caused little dose perturbation and showed good radiographic visibility. Even in the presence of a unidirectional proton beam, the dose reduction was <5%. We expect that further optimization of the gold particle concentration should lead to even lower reductions in the proton dose.

The volume of the underdosed region behind a perpendicularly aligned macroscopic gold fiducial marker was approximated from a proton radiograph (Fig. 5). To quantify the volume accurately, a 3D Monte Carlo simulation using the GEANT4 toolkit was performed with a single directional proton beam that had the same energy, width of SOBP, and position of the marker in water as the experimental setup for proton radiography 25, 26. The Monte Carlo simulation showed a similar dose distribution as the proton radiograph; it also showed that a 0.1-mL volume was irradiated behind a single macroscopic gold marker, at most below 90% of the SOBP dose. If more fiducials are used to improve the accuracy of tumor targeting, their influence will become more significant (27). However, a region below 95% of the SOBP dose did not exist for any perpendicularly aligned gold particle mixtures.

For the gold particle fiducials, the dose shadow disappearance appeared trivial because there was sufficient space between the gold particles in the fiducials to allow the protons to pass. Although the gold particles used were 25 μm in diameter, there were few CT artifacts. Smaller gold particles (e.g., gold nanoparticles) would be expected to yield even fewer CT artifacts because of the reduced periodic lattice of gold atoms and because of the multiple scattering of X-rays between the nanoparticles.

A gold particle–polymer mixture may be one of the best compositions for the clinical application of gold particle fiducials. This polymer should be human-compatible and should stably bind the gold particles. A strong candidate for this polymer is bone cement, which is used for vertebroplasty and kyphoplasty 28, 29. Bone cement would be an ideal substance for this purpose because it has sufficient mechanical strength, such as compressive, tensile, and sheer strengths (30), which would ensure that the gold particles are stably bound to the bone cement; this in turn would enable insertion of the mixture into a prostate using the conventional methods used for the insertion of gold fiducials (31). Moreover, because contrast agent materials such as barium sulfate and zirconia are included in bone cement, this would enhance the radiographic visibility of the gold particle mixtures in diagnostic X-rays. A further advantage of polymer-based mixtures is that they can be easily formed into various shapes at room temperature before curing. This would allow the formation of fiducials into complex shapes that will prevent migration in the prostate. This would also be an advantage in the development of optimal shapes for markers in other sites, such as the eyes, lungs, and breasts.

Another consideration in the use of gold particle fiducials such as the ones we studied here is that the physical properties of materials change as their size approaches the nanometer range 32, 33. Two primary factors determine these physical properties: surface effects, which cause smooth property scaling due to the fraction of atoms at the surface, and quantum effects, which show a discontinuous behavior due to quantum confinement effects in materials with delocalized electrons 33, 34. These factors also affect the chemical reactivity of materials. For microscopic particles larger than 1 μm, however, the quantum effects are negligible and the surface effects are subtle because the percentage of atoms on the surface is minuscule relative to the total number of atoms in the particles. Therefore, micrometer-sized gold particles have physical and chemical properties similar to macroscopic gold bulbs and can be regarded as nontoxic materials 33, 34. Moreover, spherical gold nanoparticles with various surface coatings have been shown to be nontoxic to human cells even when internalized 34, 35, 36.

Recently, “markerless” IGRT involving the use of kilovoltage (kV) cone-beam CT (CBCT) was studied for prostate cancer (37). When the localization performance of the prostate by soft-tissue matching with kV CBCT was compared with that achieved by fiducial marker matching, the latter proved to have better targeting accuracy, involve a simpler matching process, and show little interobserver dependency. It also eliminated the extra cost of installing a CBCT in a treatment room.

Conclusions

Our results showed that the mixtures of microscopic gold particles have good radiographic visibility and produce few CT artifacts in diagnostic X-rays. They also produce low distortion of the depth-dose distribution in the proton treatment of the prostate. Of particular note, for the gold particle mixture with the 4.9% normalized gold density, the maximum dose reduction was <5%, even when there was parallel alignment of the mixture and a unidirectional proton beam. This result appears to be superior to the earlier findings of Newhauser et al.(18), who reported an 8.6% dose reduction for small stainless steel using a laterally opposed pair treatment field technique. Our quantitative comparison of the CT artifacts associated with gold particle fiducial use indicates that they were dramatically reduced in number. Taken together, our results suggest that microscopic gold particle mixtures have excellent potential as fiducial markers in prostate cancer proton therapy.

    Citation Excerpt :

    However, as Chow and Grigorov [2] have shown, fiducials produce significant perturbations in planned dose distributions. Because perturbations tend to be larger in proton beams than in photon beams, most research in this area has focused on the impact of fiducials on proton dosimetry [3–5]. However, the effect of fiducials on photon dose distributions is not negligible; dose perturbation factors ranging from 0.72 to 1.64 have been reported [2].

  • Improving positioning in high-dose radiotherapy for prostate cancer: Safety and visibility of frequently used gold fiducial markers

    2012, International Journal of Radiation Oncology Biology Physics
    Citation Excerpt :

    Meanwhile, using alternative GFMs consisting of mixtures of microscopic gold particles and human-compatible polymers may be of value. These markers have potential as GFMs because of their good radiographic visibility, low distortion of the depth-dose distribution, and few CT artifacts (36). Another point of consideration is the “biological reaction” induced by GFM and the effect on the tumor environment.
